"# Chapter 14 — Concurrency, coroutines, async

Concurrency is when a program has multiple things going on at once.
Not always simultaneously in the physics sense — sometimes just
interleaved rapidly. But logically, more than one activity is in
flight.

This chapter is about the shapes concurrency takes in modern
languages. Threads. Coroutines. Async functions. The Amiga's
preemptive multitasking (Chapter 7) was one early home-computer
example; this chapter is about how the same problems get solved in
software today.

## Why concurrency at all

Because programs wait a lot. Reading a file waits for the disk.
Sending a network request waits for the response. Waiting for user
input. Waiting for a timer. If your program does nothing while
waiting, you're wasting time.

Also because programs often do many things that don't interfere.
Rendering the screen, playing sound, updating the game state,
listening for the keyboard — all can happen in parallel if you
arrange them right.

## Processes

A process is a running program with its own memory space. Chapter 9
of Book of Computing discussed processes in the Unix sense.

Processes are heavy. Each has its own address space. Communication
between processes requires explicit channels — pipes, files, network
sockets, or a specific kernel-provided message-passing feature.

Processes are strong isolation. One process can't corrupt another's
memory. If one crashes, others live on. That's the big benefit —
web browsers put each tab in its own process for this reason.

## Threads

A thread is like a process but shares memory with other threads in
the same program. Threads are lighter than processes (creating a
thread is faster than creating a process; switching between threads
is cheaper than switching between processes). But threads inside the
same program can step on each other's data.

The main problem with threads is shared mutable state. If two
threads write to the same variable at the same time, the result can
be corrupt in surprising ways. The fixes — locks, mutexes,
semaphores, atomic operations — are the entire subject of
concurrent programming, and they are hard.

Motoi Scheme's default runtime is single-threaded. This is a
deliberate choice: Motoi is meant to be simple enough to reason
about end-to-end. Single-threaded execution is much easier to
teach and debug.

## Coroutines

A coroutine is a function that can pause itself, save its state, and
be resumed later.

Regular functions run to completion or return. Coroutines can
`yield` a value, remember where they were, and be `resume`d from
that spot. This is very useful for expressing sequences that would
otherwise need a state machine.

A classic example — a Fibonacci coroutine:

```
(define fib-generator
  (make-coroutine
    (lambda (yield)
      (let loop ((a 0) (b 1))
        (yield a)
        (loop b (+ a b))))))

(fib-generator)   ;; => 0
(fib-generator)   ;; => 1
(fib-generator)   ;; => 1
(fib-generator)   ;; => 2
(fib-generator)   ;; => 3
(fib-generator)   ;; => 5
```

Every call resumes the coroutine at the last `yield`, runs until the
next `yield`, and returns that value. The coroutine's local
variables (`a` and `b`) are preserved between calls.

Coroutines let you express infinite sequences, lazy computations, or
long-running iterations in a natural top-to-bottom form.

Motoi Scheme supports coroutines. They're used internally by the
composer for animation timelines and by the language model for
streaming output.

## Async / await

Async / await is a coroutine-like pattern that shows up in many modern
languages (Python, JavaScript, C#, Rust, Kotlin). The idea:

```
;; JavaScript-style syntax
async function fetch_and_render(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  const data = await response.json();
  render(data);
}
```

The `await` operator pauses the function until the awaited thing
completes. The pause doesn't block the whole program — other async
functions can run in the meantime. When the awaited thing completes,
the function resumes.

Async functions are usually built on top of an event loop. The event
loop keeps track of what's currently paused waiting for what, and
when something completes, wakes up the appropriate function.

Motoi Scheme uses a similar pattern for slow operations like reading
a file:

```
(await (file/read \"data.txt\")
  (lambda (contents)
    (process contents)))
```

The runtime pauses the current computation until the file is read,
then resumes with the contents. This is not literally async/await —
Scheme's continuation-passing style expresses the same shape a
different way.

## The actor model

An actor is an autonomous unit that:
- Has its own private state.
- Communicates only by sending messages to other actors.
- Processes messages one at a time.

Actors give you concurrency without shared memory. Every actor's
state is its own. Coordination happens by messages.

The actor model was invented by Carl Hewitt and colleagues at MIT
in the early 1970s. It influenced Smalltalk (Chapter 10 of Book of
Language Ancestors). It's the concurrency model of Erlang, Elixir,
Akka, and various others.

Actors are attractive because they eliminate the whole family of
shared-memory bugs. They introduce their own set of problems
(message ordering, backpressure, actor supervision) but many people
find those easier to reason about.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Concurrency is a rich subject with many shapes:
- **Processes** for isolation.
- **Threads** for tightly-shared work (with lots of care).
- **Coroutines** for expressing sequences that pause.
- **Async/await** for I/O-bound work.
- **Actors** for message-based coordination.

Each fits different problems. None is universally best. Modern
languages usually offer several of these; you pick based on what
your program is doing.

Motoi Scheme runs single-threaded, uses coroutines for a few
internal patterns, and takes I/O in a callback / continuation style.
That is enough for the pedagogical mission. If you need serious
concurrency, you're going to use a language and runtime designed
for it — Erlang, Rust, Go, or something similar. Motoi respects
those and doesn't try to be them.")
